                "name": "Antonia Ferraro",
                "href": "/profile/Antonia-Ferraro-1"
            },
            "answer_text": "I obtained the following: Ultimately, out of the 4.5 million Italians that immigrated to the United States between the years 1880 and 1930, one out of every four was a Sicilian. The immigrants represented virtually every area in Sicily. The numbers would have been higher but for the passage of the U.S. Immigration Act of 1924. The Act reduced the number of persons allowed to immigrate to the United States from Italy to 3,845. The fact that 1 in 4 Italian immigrants was from Sicily, is probably why 1 of my four grandparents is Sicilian and the other Italian grandparents from Campania. I also married someone who has 1 grandparent from Sicily and grandparents from other regions of southern Italy. Perhaps being 1/4 Sicilian is common amongst 3rd generation Italo-Americans, but I don\u2019t have any statics on that. Read more: https://www.everyculture.com/multi/Pa-Sp/Sicilian-Americans.html#ixzz679mTKEVg ",
