                "name": "Francesco Baldessari",
                "href": "/profile/Francesco-Baldessari"
            },
            "answer_text": "Many, not all, but almost all Italian-Americans in the US come from the south of the peninsula, while most Italian-Americans in Argentina and Brazil come from the north. I am from the north, and all my relatives are there.According to a book I read years ago, there is an interesting reason for that: the different economies of the two halves of the country before unification. Southern Italy\u2019s economy was based on large estates (latifundium), which needs and produces large amounts of unskilled workers, ideal for the US industrial economy. The north has far less flat usable land per capita, so production per square unit must be higher. Northern farmers went to Argentina and Brazil bringing with them skills they hoped to use. ",
